@flexiarg writing-coherence/recursion-cheque
@title Show the Recursion at at Least One Scale, or Drop It
@keywords recursion, fractal, self-similar, scale, multi-scale, cash-it-or-drop
@audience paper authors, reviewers
@tone technical
@style pattern
@references [writing-coherence/unearned-essentially]

! conclusion: A sentence claiming that an argument applies at multiple scales — "the same argument applies within X as across X", "the structure is recursive: the same pattern holds at each level" — writes a cheque that must be cashed.  Either the paper demonstrates the claim at at least one scale, or it does not belong.  Recursion, fractality, and self-similarity are analytical devices only when they produce a result the flat view does not.
  + context: Recursion claims are attractive because they sound elegant and ambitious.  They promise that one argument covers multiple phenomena.  They are dangerous because the elegance is free — the writer pays nothing to claim recursion, and the reader has no way to check unless the paper exhibits it.  AI prose tips toward making recursion claims that the paper has set up but not demonstrated.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: generalisation claim ↔ demonstration capacity.
    Real: recursion, when genuine, is a powerful compression.  Recursion, when asserted without demonstration, is mere rhetoric.  The paper cannot have the compression without paying for it.
    Irreducible: a claim cannot simultaneously generalise across scales and decline to show any scale beyond the original.
    Active: the pull recurs whenever a paper's main argument feels "big enough" to generalise but has only been shown in one form.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Cash at one scale: keep the recursion claim; add one concrete instance at a second scale.  Show the argument biting at the smaller or larger scale the claim names.  The recursion is now earned by exhibition.
    (2) Cash at both scales: if the recursion is structurally central (not decorative), demonstrate it at both.  This is the highest-commitment path and is appropriate when the recursion IS the result.
    (3) Drop the claim: if no scale-shifted demonstration is available, remove the recursion sentence.  The paper still has everything it had before; what it loses is a claim it could not back.
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: every recursion or multi-scale claim in the paper is accompanied by at least one concrete demonstration beyond the primary scale.  Failing when: "the same argument applies at scale Y" appears without a demonstration at scale Y.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - Undemonstrated within-X: "the same logic that holds across institutions holds within them" with no within-institution case.
    - Asserted fractality: "the structure is recursive / fractal / self-similar" as a closing gesture.
    - Free elegance: recursion claim appears only in the conclusion, not in the body.
    - Circular defence: when questioned, the writer points to the main argument as evidence the recursion holds — but the main argument is at the primary scale only.
